The current federal standard for independent contractor classification is based on the Fair Labor Standards Act (FLSA) and the Department of Labor's (DOL) guidance on independent contractor misclassification enforcement. According to the DOL, an individual is considered an independent contractor if they meet the following criteria:

* They are free from the control and direction of the hiring entity in connection with the performance of the work (FLSA, 29 U.S.C. § 203(g));
* They perform work that is outside the usual course of the hiring entity's business (FLSA, 29 U.S.C. § 203(g));
* They are customarily engaged in an independently established trade, occupation, or business of the same nature as that involved in the work performed (FLSA, 29 U.S.C. § 203(g));
* They are responsible for their own expenses and have the opportunity to realize a profit or loss (DOL, [7]);
* They have control over the means and manner of performing the work (DOL, [7]).

The DOL has also issued guidance on the "economic reality" test, which considers the following factors to determine whether an individual is an employee or an independent contractor:

* The nature and degree of control exercised by the hiring entity;
* The degree of skill required for the work;
* The permanence of the working relationship;
* The amount of investment made by the individual;
* The opportunity for profit or loss;
* The degree of permanence of the working relationship;
* The degree of integration of the individual's work into the hiring entity's business (DOL, [7]).

The penalties for misclassification can be severe and include:

* Fines levied by the DOL, IRS, and state agencies, which can exceed millions depending on the severity of the infractions (ADP, [10]);
* Class action lawsuits, which can result in significant damages and attorney's fees (Pillsbury, [6]);
* Back pay and benefits owed to misclassified employees (DOL, [7]);
* Interest on back pay and benefits owed (DOL, [7]);
* Liquidated damages, which can be up to 100% of the back pay and benefits owed (FLSA, 29 U.S.C. § 216(c)).

In addition, employers may also face reputational damage and loss of business due to misclassification.

